Savory  Onion and Leek Tart  Recipe

Ingredients: 

1 premade pie crust, thawed 
2 large onions, thinly sliced;
2 large leeks, thinly sliced;
3  cloves  garlic, minced;
4 tbsp   olive oil; 
 salt & pepper   to taste;
1 cup grated Gruyère cheese; 
1  egg beaten; 
1 tsp dried thyme;

Instructions:

1. Preheat your oven to  375°F (190°C). 

2. In a large skillet over medium  heat, add olive oil, minced garlic, diced onions, and sliced  leeks. Cook until  caramelized, stirring occasionally,  about  20 minutes. Season with salt and pepper to  taste.  

3. While the veggies are  cooking, roll out  the pre-made pie  crust  on a  lightly floured surface until it’s approximately 12 inches in  diameter.  Transfer the dough to a 9 or  10 inch tart  pan, trimming off any  excess dough. Prick   the bottom  of the  crust with a fork. 

4. Once the veggies   are  done cooking, remove them from heat and sprinkle in the grated Gruyère cheese. Stir well  to combine. 

5. Pour the  vegetable mixture into the pie crust, spreading  it evenly. Drizzle the beaten egg  over the top, then sprinkle on the   dried thyme. 

6. Place the tart pan on a baking sheet  and bake in the oven for 35-40 minutes, or until  the center is set and the top is golden brown. Allow the tart to cool before slicing and  serving. Enjoy!

The term peace pipe  (or calumet) refers to a  ceremonial smoking pipe   used by  Native Americans  in North America, and sometimes  also by  First Nations peoples in  Canada. It was often made out of clay or stone, but  could be carved from wood as well. In some cases  it  would have been decorated with feathers, shells, or other decorations.  A peace pipe ceremony involved two parties who were at odds with each other;   they smoked together from the same pipe, which symbolized their desire   for peace between them. This practice has become known as passing the  peace.

##  History[edit]

Peace pipes are  not unique to any one tribe or nation, although certain tribes may have   had more elaborate rituals associated  with them  than others did.^{[1]} They  were   commonly used among many different groups throughout  North  America during times when  there was  conflict between nations or individuals within those nations.^{[2]}  For example,  if two warring factions wanted to make peace  after fighting over land  rights then both sides might agree  on using this  method so  that everyone could see how  serious they were about ending hostilities once and for all!^{[3]}

In addition to being used as part of formal negotiations between rival groups such  as tribes  or clans within larger  tribal confederacies like  Iroquois League (Haudenosaunee),^{[4]} these ceremonies were also held between individual members within families where disputes had arisen due either personal  differences  between siblings/cousins etc., or because someone had committed an offense  against another person's property rights.^{[5]}

